Such protests are common to all times of wealth and luxury. Another example is 3, 6. Augustus tried to restrain the growth of private extrava- gance, and to restore the agricultural prosperity of Italy. Some editors have wished, therefore, to connect this ode with the date (28 B.C.) at which Octavian assumed the duties of censor, and indeed it is quite pos- sible that it was written at the emperor's request. The verses are stiff. and bear the marks of being made to order. The position here after 14, from which in some manuscripts it is not separated, is a natural one,

for it continues the attack on the folly of great wealth.

The ode is,

however, wholly impersonal, not even the indefinite second person being

used, and lacks the poetica] quality of 14.
